amine the resources these two traditions can offer one another. By bringing the relationship between these two critical fields of thought to the forefront, the book will encourage scholars to engage in new dialogues about how each can inform the other. If contemporary philosophy is troubled by the fact that it can be too limited, too closed, too white, too male, then this groundbreaking book confronts and challenges these problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aContinental philosophy. 0aFeminism. 0aWomanism. 0aWomen, Black. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBelle, Kathryn Sophia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Maria del Guadalupe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Maria del Guadalupe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGines, Kathryn T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Kathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuy-Sheftall, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Robin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Emily S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMann, Anika Maaza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcano, Donna-Dale L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcano, Donna-Dale L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerp